{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17130"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17130"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.2,0.08,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77264"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9820"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62771"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5003"},{"type":"tags","id":"5004"},{"type":"tags","id":"5005"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77264"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUnfractionated heparin and low molecular weight heparin are anticoagulant medications commonly used for prevention and treatment of thromboembolism. Both medications require antithrombin III as a cofactor but differ in their relative effects on coagulation factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how unfractionated heparin differs from low molecular weight heparin in its mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Greater inhibition of both factor Xa and thrombin","Selective inhibition of factor Xa only","Selective inhibition of thrombin only","Greater inhibition of protein C pathway","Selective inhibition of tissue factor pathway"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key difference is that unfractionated heparin causes \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater inhibition of both factor Xa and thrombin\u003C/strong\u003E compared to low molecular weight heparin, which predominantly affects factor Xa. This broader activity profile explains why unfractionated heparin requires more careful monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective inhibition of factor Xa only\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the primary mechanism of low molecular weight heparin rather than unfractionated heparin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective inhibition of thrombin only\u003C/strong\u003E - Unfractionated heparin has significant effects on both thrombin and factor Xa, not just thrombin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreater inhibition of protein C pathway\u003C/strong\u003E - While heparins can have some effect on the protein C pathway, this is not their primary mechanism of action or a key difference between the two types.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective inhibition of tissue factor pathway\u003C/strong\u003E - Neither form of heparin acts directly on the tissue factor pathway; they work through antithrombin III-mediated inhibition of coagulation factors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe broader inhibition profile of unfractionated heparin results in less predictable pharmacokinetics and necessitates regular monitoring of activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT), unlike low molecular weight heparin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unfractionated heparin acts by binding to and activating antithrombin III, which then inhibits factors Xa and IIa (thrombin).","Low molecular weight heparin primarily inhibits factor Xa using antithrombin III as a cofactor, with less effect on thrombin.","Unlike unfractionated heparin, low molecular weight heparin has more predictable pharmacokinetics and does not require the same level of monitoring."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62771"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17130"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62771"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:02:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:02:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9820"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77264"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":nul